    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1965-03-08T18:55:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1965-03-08T18:55:00-05:00" n="102"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d102">
                <head>102. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in the Soviet Union</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d102fn1">Source: National Archives and Records
                        Administration, <gloss target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Files 1964–66,
                        POL 23–8 <gloss target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss>. Confidential. Drafted by
                            <persName corresp="#p_HDH1">Henry</persName>, cleared in draft by
                            <persName corresp="#p_DRH1">Davis</persName> and <gloss target="#t_SES1"
                            >SES</gloss>, and approved and initialed by <persName corresp="#p_TLE1"
                            >Thompson</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1965-03-08T18:55:00-05:00">March 8, 1965, 6:55 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2400. For Ambassador from Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_TLE1"
                        >Thompson</persName>. Embtel 2607.<note n="2" xml:id="d102fn2">
                        <ref target="#d101">Document 101</ref>.</note> Appreciate your suggestions
                    and particularly agree with last two paragraphs. All of us here feel deeply that
                    we must, as you suggest, keep “channels of communication open during fluid and
                    critical period.”</p>
                <p>With regard to your suggestions, there are no forthcoming public appearances by
                    Soviet Embassy staff except one of which sponsors are left-wing groups which
                    would be unlikely to cancel. We shall, however, attempt to ensure that exchange
                    program sponsors point out to their Soviet contacts on appropriate occasions
                    that attacks on Embassy can damage exchange program and U.S.-<gloss
                        target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss> relations. However, our position has been
                    somewhat weakened by recent attack on Soviet Embassy here.</p>
                <p>In general, we consider it important to avoid getting into a visa war with the
                        <gloss target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss>. We are glad for that reason that you
                    merely postponed the Soviet group rather than refusing visas outright. Serious
                    as these attacks are, they are less important than such substantive issues as
                    S.E. Asia, disarmament and European security, on which progress requires free
                        U.S.-<gloss target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss> interchange. Therefore, we must
                    strive in our own interests to keep a dialogue going even in the face of Soviet
                    actions against U.S. policy in third areas or unpleasant incidents like the
                    attack on the Embassy.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RD1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Rusk</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
